6
1 Sec. 15. (a) The unit shall contract with the district management
2 association designated in the district plan to administer and
3 implement the district's activities and improvements.
4 (b) The district management association may be either an
5 existing nonprofit corporation or a newly formed nonprofit
6 corporation. If the district management association is a new
7 nonprofit corporation created to manage the district, the certificate
8 of incorporation or bylaws of the district management association
9 shall provide for voting representation of owners within the
10 district. If the district management association is an existing
11 nonprofit corporation, the existing nonprofit corporation may
12 create a committee of district owners or owners' representatives.
13 (c) The district management association may make
14 recommendations to the unit's legislative body with respect to any
15 matter involving or relating to the district.
16 (d) The unit's legislative body, for any consideration that it
17 considers appropriate, may license or grant to the district
18 management association the right to undertake or permit
19 commercial activities or other private uses of the streets or other
20 parts of the district in which the unit has any real property
21 interest.
22 Sec. 16. (a) A district may issue bonds to provide improvements.
23 The term of any bonds issued may not exceed ten (10) years. If a
24 district is renewed under section 17 of this chapter, the term of any
25 bonds issued may not exceed ten (10) years from the date of
26 renewal.
27 (b) Bonds issued under this chapter do not constitute an
28 indebtedness of the unit within the meaning of a constitutional or
29 statutory debt limitation.
30 Sec. 17. (a) The initial term for a district shall be at least three
31 (3) years and not more than ten (10) years.
32 (b) A district may be renewed for one (1) additional period of
33 not more than ten (10) years by following the procedures for the
34 initial establishment of a district as set forth in sections 9 through
35 13 of this chapter.
36 (c) If a district is renewed, any remaining revenues derived from
37 the levy of a special assessment, or any revenues derived from the
38 sale of assets acquired with the revenues, shall be transferred to the
39 renewed district. The following apply to the transfer of any
40 remaining revenues of a renewed district:
41 (1) If the renewed district includes a business not included in
42 the prior district, the remaining revenues shall be spent to
2026 IN 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

7
1 benefit only the business in the prior district.
2 (2) If the renewed district does not include a business included
3 in the prior district, the remaining revenues attributable to
4 the parcel shall be refunded to the owners of the business by
5 applying the method the district used under section 11 of this
6 chapter to calculate the special assessment before the renewal.
7 (d) The boundaries, special assessments, improvements, or
8 activities of a renewed district are not required to be the same as
9 the original or prior district.
10 Sec. 18. An ordinance adopted under section 13 of this chapter
11 may be amended if notice of the proposed amendment is published
12 and mailed in the manner provided by section 12 of this chapter.
13 However, if an amendment proposes to:
14 (1) levy a new or increased special assessment;
15 (2) change the district's boundaries; or
16 (3) issue a new bond;
17 the unit's legislative body shall require compliance with the
18 procedures set forth in sections 9 through 13 of this chapter before
19 amending the ordinance.
20 Sec. 19. (a) During the operation of the district, there shall be a
21 thirty (30) day period, beginning one (1) year after the date of the
22 district's establishment and in each year thereafter, in which the
23 owners may request dissolution of the district in accordance with
24 this section.
25 (b) After a public hearing before the unit's legislative body, the
26 legislative body may dissolve a district by ordinance in either of the
27 following circumstances:
28 (1) If the legislative body finds there has been
29 misappropriation of funds, malfeasance, or a violation of law
30 in connection with the management of the district.
31 (2) At any time during the annual thirty (30) day period
32 described in subsection (a).
33 (c) Upon the written petitions of the owners or authorized
34 representatives of businesses in the district that pay fifty percent
35 (50%) or more of the special assessments levied, the unit's
36 legislative body shall pass a resolution of intention to dissolve the
37 district.
38 (d) The unit's legislative body shall first adopt a resolution of
39 intention to dissolve the district before the public hearing to
40 dissolve a district under this section. The resolution of intention
41 must include each of the following items:
42 (1) The reason for the dissolution.
2026 IN 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

8
1 (2) The time and place of the public hearing.
2 (3) A proposal to dispose of any assets acquired with the
3 revenues of the special assessments levied within the district.
4 The notice of the hearing on the resolution of intent to dissolve the
5 district shall be published in the manner provided by IC 5-3-1 and
6 must also be given by mail to the owner of each business subject to
7 a special assessment in the district. The legislative body shall
8 conduct the public hearing on the resolution of intention to dissolve
9 the district not later than thirty (30) days after the date the notice
10 is mailed to the assessed owners.
11 (e) The public hearing to dissolve the district shall be held not
12 more than sixty (60) days after the date of the adoption of the
13 resolution of intention.
14 (f) A dissolution of a district under this section has the effect of
15 repealing the ordinance adopted under section 13 of this chapter
16 that established the district.
17 Sec. 20. (a) The district management association shall submit an
18 annual report to the legislative body and the fiscal body before
19 January 1 of each year, beginning in the year after the first year of
20 the district's establishment.
21 (b) The report shall contain the following information:
22 (1) The use of revenue collected from special assessments
23 levied under this chapter for that year.
24 (2) The activities and improvements to be provided for the
25 ensuing year and an estimate of the cost of providing the
26 activities and improvements for the ensuing year.
27 (3) The estimated amount of any surplus or deficit revenues
28 to be carried over from the prior year.
29 Sec. 21. (a) Upon the dissolution or expiration without renewal
30 of a district, any remaining revenues, after all outstanding debts
31 are paid, derived from the:
32 (1) levy of special assessments; or
33 (2) sale of assets acquired with the revenues of the district or
34 from bond reserve funds or construction funds;
35 shall be refunded to the owners located within the district on or
36 before the date of the district's dissolution or expiration without
37 renewal.
38 (b) The amount of the refund provided under subsection (a) to
39 an owner shall be determined by applying the method the district
40 used under section 11 of this chapter to calculate the special
41 assessment in the year:
42 (1) in which the district was dissolved or allowed to expire
2026 IN 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

9
1 without renewal; or
2 (2) before the district was dissolved or allowed to expire
3 without renewal if a special assessment had not been levied.
4 However, in lieu of providing a refund, the unit's legislative body
5 may instead elect to spend any remaining revenues on activities
6 and improvements specified in the ordinance that established the
7 district before its dissolution or expiration without renewal.
8 (c) Any liabilities incurred by the district are not an obligation
9 of the unit and are payable solely from the collection of special
10 assessments deposited in the special fund under section 14 of this
11 chapter and other revenues of the district.
12 Sec. 22. Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter,
13 special assessments levied to pay the principal and interest on any
14 bonds issued under this chapter may not be reduced or terminated
15 if doing so would interfere with the timely retirement of the debt.
